).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,261,383,409]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Male</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[278,369,384,410]" captionStart="FIGURES 32 – 36" captionStartId="14.[151,273,1598,1622]" captionTargetBox="[151,1436,197,1574]" captionTargetId="figure@14.[151,1436,197,1575]" captionTargetPageId="14" captionText="FIGURES 32 – 36. Adults of Perittia species. 32, P. gnoma sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005176; 33, P. falciferella sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005180; 34, P. spatulata sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: 000005159; 35, P. spatulata sp. n., female, paratype. Specimen ID: 000005172; 36, P. tantilla sp. n., male, holotype. Specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5148. Scale bar 1 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189258/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<number box="[335,369,384,410]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="32.0">32</number>
</figureCitation>
). Forewing length 2.3–2.6 mm; wingspan 5.2–5.9 mm (n= 
<number box="[1076,1092,384,410]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2.0">2</number>
). Head: Vertex and neck tuft pale ochre, some scales with brownish-black tips; background layer of frons with some metallic lustre; labial palpus very short and straight, yellowish white above, fuscous below; scape broader than flagellum, covered with yellowish-white scales with brownish-black tips; flagellum rather broad, unicolourous, brownish grey. Ground colour of thorax, tegula, and forewing pale ochre to ochre, mottled due to brownish-black tips of scales. Denser brownish-black scales forming two irregular patches: one in basal part of wing; other extending obliquely at 
<number box="[300,315,616,642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[324,337,616,642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="5.0">5</number>
of costa towards tornus of wing. Brownish-black scales forming two small spots: one at 
<number box="[1398,1413,616,642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2.0">2</number>
/ 
<number box="[1423,1436,616,642]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="5.0">5</number>
from wing base and other at 
<number box="[484,499,654,680]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="3.0">3</number>
/ 
<number box="[510,525,654,680]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="5.0">5</number>
. Fringe scales brownish grey with irregularly scattered brownish black-tipped scales. Hindwing blackish brown, its fringe brownish grey.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" box="[197,426,731,758]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,288,731,757]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Female</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,378,770,796]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Male genitalia</emphasis>
(
<figureCitation box="[396,544,770,796]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 40" captionStartId="15.[151,270,1617,1641]" captionTargetBox="[173,1416,202,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,90,1593]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 40. Perittia gnoma sp. n., male genitalia. 37, valvae, juxta and phallus; 38, uncus, tegumen, gnathos and vinculum. Holotype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 473, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5176. Scale bar 0.1 mm. 39, valva; 40, apical part of phallus and juxta lobes (a, juxta lobe). Paratype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 474, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5177." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189259/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs. 
<number box="[464,544,770,796]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="38.5" valueMax="40.0" valueMin="37.0">37–40</number>
</figureCitation>
). Uncus short, posterior margin weakly sclerotized. Basal arms of gnathos rather long; spinose knob of gnathos wider than long, tapered towards apex. Valva short and broad; costa slightly convex; sacculus convex, distally strongly concave, forming sharp angle when meeting cucullus; cucullus narrow and long, about 
<number box="[532,547,886,912]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="4.0">4</number>
times longer than broad, apex with small upcurved tooth, inner surface with long, slender and acute process (
<figureCitation box="[543,633,925,951]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 40" captionStartId="15.[151,270,1617,1641]" captionTargetBox="[173,1416,202,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,90,1593]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 40. Perittia gnoma sp. n., male genitalia. 37, valvae, juxta and phallus; 38, uncus, tegumen, gnathos and vinculum. Holotype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 473, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5176. Scale bar 0.1 mm. 39, valva; 40, apical part of phallus and juxta lobes (a, juxta lobe). Paratype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 474, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5177." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189259/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<number box="[599,633,925,951]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="39.0">39</number>
</figureCitation>
). Ventral shield of juxta lightly sclerotized, elliptical with broadlyrounded proximal end and weakly-concave distal end, about 
<number box="[905,916,964,990]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="1.0">1</number>
/ 
<number box="[927,944,964,990]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2.0">2</number>
length of phallus; juxta lobes short and narrow. Digitate processes not developed. Vinculum U-shaped, without saccus. Phallus short, about 
<number box="[1349,1364,1002,1028]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="4.0">4</number>
times longer than broad, ventral wall with long and narrow incision in apical part, dorsal wall tapering, apex pointed, weakly sclerotized; vesica with few tiny spines and two clusters of large cornuti (
<number box="[1272,1319,1080,1106]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="2.5" valueMax="3.0" valueMin="2.0">2–3</number>
and 
<number box="[1380,1428,1080,1106]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="6.5" valueMax="7.0" valueMin="6.0">6–7</number>
) slightly varying in size.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="biology_ecology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" box="[197,427,1157,1183]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,289,1157,1183]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Biology</emphasis>
. Unknown.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" box="[197,1264,1195,1222]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,360,1195,1221]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Flight period</emphasis>
. Based upon the two specimens available, adults fly in late March and April.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,351,1234,1260]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Distribution</emphasis>
. So far this species is known only from the Arabuko Sokoke Forest Reserve in the Coastal Province of 
<collectingCountry box="[294,370,1273,1299]" name="Kenya" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Kenya</collectingCountry>
(
<figureCitation box="[387,468,1273,1299]" captionStart="FIGURES 1 – 4" captionStartId="2.[151,269,1176,1200]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,297,1155]" captionTargetId="figure@2.[151,1436,297,1155]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="FIGURES 1 – 4. Collecting localities in Kenya. 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell’s Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189249/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Figs. 
<number box="[453,468,1273,1299]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="1.15">1</number>
</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[482,514,1273,1299]" captionStart="FIGURE 15" captionStartId="6.[151,259,1145,1169]" captionTargetBox="[409,1178,212,1101]" captionTargetId="figure@6.[390,1196,194,1121]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURE 15. Collecting localities of Elachistinae species in Kenya: 1, Arabuko Sokoke Forest National Park; 2, Aberdares National Park; 3, Hell's Gate National Park; 4, Kakamega Forest National Reserve." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189252/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">15</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="etymology">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,330,1311,1337]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Etymology</emphasis>
. The species name is derived from the Latin 
<emphasis box="[865,956,1312,1337]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">gnomus</emphasis>
(dwarf), referring to the small body size of this species.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="16" pageNumber="17" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="16.[151,1437,152,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[197,311,1389,1415]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">Remarks</emphasis>
. This species, along with 
<taxonomicName box="[615,753,1389,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="spatulata">
<emphasis box="[615,753,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">P. spatulata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName box="[810,923,1389,1414]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" genus="Perittia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tantilla">
<emphasis box="[810,923,1389,1414]" italics="true" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">P. tantilla</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, differs from all other known species of the 
<taxonomicName box="[151,294,1428,1454]" class="Insecta" family="Elachistidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Elachistinae">Elachistinae</taxonomicName>
by the direction of the spines on the apical knob of the gnathos. The tips of the gnathos spines are directed anteriorly rather than posteriorly in all other species. In the male genitalia the juxta is fused with the phallus, therefore during preparation, if the phallus is removed, the juxta lobes can be separated from the juxta along with the phallus (
<figureCitation box="[426,515,1544,1570]" captionStart="FIGURES 37 – 40" captionStartId="15.[151,270,1617,1641]" captionTargetBox="[173,1416,202,1592]" captionTargetId="figure@15.[151,1436,90,1593]" captionTargetPageId="15" captionText="FIGURES 37 – 40. Perittia gnoma sp. n., male genitalia. 37, valvae, juxta and phallus; 38, uncus, tegumen, gnathos and vinculum. Holotype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 473, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5176. Scale bar 0.1 mm. 39, valva; 40, apical part of phallus and juxta lobes (a, juxta lobe). Paratype, gen. prep. MRAC / KMMA 0 0 474, specimen ID: RMCA ENT 0 0 0 0 0 5177." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/189259/files/figure.png" pageId="16" pageNumber="17">
Fig. 
<number box="[481,515,1544,1570]" pageId="16" pageNumber="17" value="40.0">40</number>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
